Choosing a region.

The most concrete first decision AWS forces on you is which region to deploy in. Four factors drive it, in roughly this order of weight.

First, compliance and data residency. Some regulations require data to stay inside a particular country or economic zone. This factor is often non-negotiable, so it comes first.

Second, latency. The closest region to your users wins. If your users are spread across continents, you design for multiple regions, with Route fifty-three and CloudFront in front to route each user to the nearest one.

Third, service availability. New services launch in you-ess-east-one and a handful of other regions first, then spread out over months or years. Before you commit, verify that every service you need actually exists in your target region.

Fourth, pricing. Costs vary modestly between regions. Treat this as a tiebreaker, not a driver. Let compliance, latency, and availability decide first, and let price settle a close call.
